{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513628"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:11:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:11:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12168"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12168"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.74,0.13,0.04,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4696"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78142"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4696"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12168"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63564"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1164"},{"type":"tags","id":"1708"},{"type":"tags","id":"3202"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7162"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7280"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7282"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26774"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78142"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department because of a sudden inability to speak. His wife reports that during breakfast he suddenly leaned backward, grunted incoherently and fell on the floor. She noticed that he was having trouble moving his right arm and so she called an ambulance. He is a cigarette smoker and had a history of hypertension. On examination, his blood pressure is 218/116 mmHg, pulse 86/min, temperature 37.3\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and respiratory rate 16/min. The neurological examination shows a flat right nasolabial fold and decreased movements of the right side of his face, sparing the forehead. There is no right arm movement, except for slight flexion toward a painful stimulus. He can raise his right leg off the bed, but not against resistance. He can not articulate or repeat words and cannot follow commands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagram shows the cerebral vasculature (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Occlusion of which of the following arteries would lead to this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A","B","C","D","E"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has risk factors for vascular diseases (elderly and hypertensive) and presents with sudden onset of focal neurologic deficit which suggests cerebrovascular stroke. The neurologic examination shows a right upper motor neuron facial lesion (affection of the lower half of the face), right sided weakness which is more severe in the right upper limb, and global aphasia. Occlusion of the \u003Cstrong\u003Emiddle cerebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E (\u003Cstrong\u003Eartery labelled B\u003C/strong\u003E) would explain these neurologic deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOcclusion of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eartery labelled A\u003C/strong\u003E (anterior cerebral artery) would result in apathy, abulia, and contralateral motor/sensory loss in leg more than in arm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOcclusion of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eartery labelled C \u003C/strong\u003E(posterior cerebral artery) typically cause visual symptoms such as homonymous hemianopia or quadrantanopia and sensory deficits but seldom paralysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOcclusion of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eartery labelled D\u003C/strong\u003E (anterior inferior cerebellar artery) would result in ipsilateral deafness, limb ataxia and facial motor/sensory loss with contralateral decreased pain/temperature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOcclusion of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eartery labelled E \u003C/strong\u003E(posterior inferior cerebellar artery) would result in ipsilateral palatal weakness, limb ataxia and Horner syndrome with contralateral decreased pain/temperature.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Occlusion of the middle cerebral artery results in contralateral motor and sensory deficits involving the face and arm, and to a lesser extent, the leg. There may be a homonymous hemianopia, and conjugate eye deviation toward the side of the lesion.","If occlusion occurs in the dominant hemisphere, this causes global aphasia, while occlusion in the nondominant hemisphere results in contralateral hemispatial neglect.","The middle cerebral artery is the most commonly affected artery in ischaemic strokes, often leading to significant neurological deficits due to its extensive supply to the lateral aspects of the cerebral cortex."],"references":["Pare JR, Kahn JH. Basic neuroanatomy and stroke syndromes. Emerg Med Clin North Am. 2012 Aug;30(3):601-15. doi: 10.1016/j.emc.2012.05.004. PMID: 22974640. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22974640/","Navarro-Orozco D, S\u00e1nchez-Manso JC. Neuroanatomy, Middle Cerebral Artery. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526002/","Navarro-Orozco D, S\u00e1nchez-Manso JC. Neuroanatomy, Middle Cerebral Artery. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526002/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63564"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12168"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17575"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17575"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1141c07a-bd97-4a6f-9c01-89b16270a415.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1141c07a-bd97-4a6f-9c01-89b16270a415.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1302,"height":1424}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63564"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T14:27:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T14:28:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4696"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78142"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.e